Here's how to implement all three requirements:

## 1. Custom "Cancel" Back Button (in your page XAML)

```xml
<!-- EditProductPage.xaml -->
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

## 2 & 3. Navigation Guard with Confirmation Dialog (in AppShell.xaml.cs)

```csharp
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    // Only intercept back navigation from EditProductPage
    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop
        && Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
        && page.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.CurrentPage.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();  // Cancel navigation ‚Äî user stays on page

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

## The ViewModel's CancelCommand

```csharp
[RelayCommand]
private async Task Cancel()
{
    if (HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        bool discard = await Shell.Current.CurrentPage.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "Discard changes?",
            "Discard", "Stay");
        if (!discard) return;
    }

    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

**Key points:**

- `GetDeferral()` is required because the confirmation dialog is async ‚Äî without it, navigation completes before the user answers.
- `args.Cancel()` stops the navigation if the user chooses "Stay".
- `BackButtonBehavior.Command` handles taps on the custom "Cancel" button, while `OnNavigating` catches the system/swipe back gesture.
